#compdef omc
# =============================================================================
# omc — The OpenModelica Compiler/Interpreter — translates Modelica
#       source code (.mo, .mof) and MetaModelica scripts (.mos) to
#       C/C++, then optionally builds and runs executable simulations
#       of cyber-physical systems (mechanical, electrical, hydraulic,
#       thermal, chemical, biological models with continuous-time
#       ODEs/DAEs + discrete-event hybrid behavior).  Modelica is the
#       de-facto industry-standard equation-based object-oriented
#       modeling language used in automotive, aerospace, energy, and
#       robotics simulation — the "MATLAB Simulink for engineers who
#       want open source."  OpenModelica is the canonical open-source
#       Modelica implementation maintained by the Open Source Modelica
#       Consortium (OSMC) at Linköping University.
#
# Author:  Open Source Modelica Consortium (OSMC), originally created
#          at PELAB (Programming Environment Laboratory) of the Dept.
#          of Computer and Information Science (IDA) at Linköping
#          University.  Lead designers include Peter Fritzson (PhD
#          advisor and prolific Modelica author/textbook writer).
#          Active development since the early 2000s — OpenModelica
#          predates most modern open-source compilers and has been in
#          continuous industrial+academic use for 20+ years.
# Source:  https://github.com/OpenModelica/OpenModelica
# CLI:     doc/manpages/omc.1 + Compiler/Util/Flags.mo
#          (MetaModelica-based flag-registration system — the
#           OpenModelica compiler is itself written in MetaModelica
#           (a Modelica extension with imperative + functional
#           constructs designed specifically for compiler
#           construction).  The argv parser is hand-rolled in
#           MetaModelica, dispatching on `+`-prefixed compiler flags
#           and `-`-prefixed RML/runtime flags.)
# Library: OpenModelica MetaModelica `Flags` module + RML runtime
#          argv parser
#          (`+`-prefix for omcOptions, `-`-prefix for runtimeOptions
#           — distinct two-prefix convention inherited from RML
#           (Relational Meta-Language, the predecessor of
#           MetaModelica))
# License: GPL-3.0 / OSMC-PL (dual-licensed)
# Status:  Active — 1317+ stars on OpenModelica/OpenModelica; the
#          flagship implementation of the Modelica modeling language,
#          used in academic + industrial settings worldwide.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 65TH DOCUMENTED LANGUAGE
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# its 65TH LANGUAGE — Modelica / MetaModelica.  OpenModelica's `omc`
# joins the corpus as a single-instance language (Modelica=1) via its
# self-hosted MetaModelica `Flags` module argv parser.  Taxonomy now
# spans 268 cross-language CLI library variants across 65 documented
# languages.
#
# Leaderboard unchanged: Rust=39 / Go=39 / TS-Node=39 (three-way tie at
# 39 preserved from R528).  Modelica=1 (new — 65th language entry).
#
# This is the FIRST documented EQUATION-BASED MODELING LANGUAGE in the
# taxonomy.  Every other documented language is procedural / functional
# / logic / concatenative — all targeting general computation.
# Modelica is fundamentally different: programs are SYSTEMS OF
# DIFFERENTIAL-ALGEBRAIC EQUATIONS (DAEs) that the compiler must
# symbolically reorder, index-reduce, and translate to numerical
# solver calls.  No other documented language has a compiler whose
# central task is symbolic DAE manipulation.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R526 owo-colors → R527 fatih/color → R528
# chalk completing the terminal-coloring triple) followed by 1 NEW
# LANGUAGE (R529 Modelica/omc — THIS).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS MODELICA AND WHY IS OMC THE 65TH LANGUAGE?
#
# Modelica (https://modelica.org, formally specified by the Modelica
# Association) is an OBJECT-ORIENTED EQUATION-BASED MODELING LANGUAGE
# for cyber-physical systems.  Created in 1996 by an international
# consortium including Hilding Elmqvist (Dymola), Peter Fritzson
# (Linköping U), Martin Otter (DLR), and ~30 other modeling
# specialists.  Modelica was designed as the LANGUAGE-LEVEL successor
# to bespoke per-discipline modeling languages (ALLAN, ASCEND, Dymola,
# NMF, ObjectMath, OMOLA, SIDOPS+, Smile, U.L.M., VHDL-AMS).
#
# Modelica's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. EQUATION-BASED — Programs are sets of equations, not assignments.
#      The Modelica `equation` section contains declarations like
#      `der(x) = -k*x + F` (a first-order ODE) or `R*I = V` (Ohm's
#      law).  The compiler symbolically:
#         a) Performs Pantelides' index-reduction algorithm on the
#            high-index DAE system
#         b) Tarjan's strongly-connected-components analysis on the
#            variable-equation bipartite graph
#         c) BLT (Block Lower Triangular) sorting to find solvable
#            subsystems
#         d) Symbolic differentiation, simplification, and code
#            generation to C
#         e) Linkage to numerical ODE/DAE solvers (DASSL, IDA, SUNDIALS)
#      Compare imperative languages: Python `x = x + 1` is an
#      assignment.  Modelica `x = x + 1` is the equation x equals
#      x+1, which has solution x = ∞ (or no solution; the compiler
#      reports a unit-mismatch error).
#
#   2. OBJECT-ORIENTED with MULTIPLE INHERITANCE — Models are classes
#      with `connector` ports specifying flow + potential variables
#      (in electrical: `voltage` potential + `current` flow; in
#      mechanical: `position` potential + `force` flow).  Library
#      models compose via `connect(componentA.flange_b,
#      componentB.flange_a)` declarations that generate KCL (current
#      sum to zero) and KVL (voltage equal) equations automatically.
#      Multiple inheritance lets a `RotationalSpring` extend both
#      `TwoFlangesRotational` (mechanical interface) and
#      `PartialCompliantSpring` (compliance behavior).
#
#   3. HYBRID DISCRETE + CONTINUOUS — Modelica models smoothly mix
#      continuous ODEs/DAEs with discrete state machines via `when`
#      events, `pre()`/`reinit()` builtins, and the `Modelica.
#      StateMachines` library.  A car simulation can have continuous
#      tire-grip equations while the gearbox is a discrete 6-state
#      automaton triggered by RPM thresholds.  No other documented
#      language compiler has this dual semantics.
#
#   4. INDUSTRY-STANDARD STANDARD LIBRARY — The Modelica Standard
#      Library (MSL) ships 1300+ components organized by physics
#      domain: Mechanics.Translational, Mechanics.Rotational,
#      Electrical.Analog, Electrical.Digital, Thermal.HeatTransfer,
#      Fluid.Pipes, Magnetic.FluxTubes, etc.  This is what makes
#      Modelica practical for industry — engineers compose simulations
#      from library components, not from scratch.
#
#   5. INDUSTRIAL ADOPTION — Modelica's commercial implementations
#      (Dassault Systèmes Dymola, Wolfram SystemModeler, ANSYS Twin
#      Builder, ESI SimulationX, Maplesoft MapleSim) are used at every
#      major automaker (BMW, Audi, Volvo, Toyota, Ford, GM, Tesla),
#      every major aerospace company (Boeing, Airbus, Embraer, Lockheed
#      Martin, NASA, ESA), and many energy and process companies.
#      OpenModelica is the open-source alternative that interoperates
#      with the same `.mo` model files.
#
# Modelica's relationship to other documented languages:
#
#   * Like Haskell — strongly-typed, expression-oriented, declarative
#   * Like Coq / Lean — symbolic manipulation is central to compilation
#   * Like SQL — declarative, set-of-constraints semantics rather than
#                step-by-step execution
#   * Like VHDL / Verilog — hardware-description-language-style
#                physical-system specification with connector ports
#   * Unlike ALL of the above — equation-based DAE semantics with
#     symbolic index reduction; the compiler IS a CAS (computer algebra
#     system).  No other documented language has this property.
#
# MetaModelica (in which omc itself is implemented):
#
#   * Modelica extension with imperative + functional features
#   * Designed at PELAB specifically for compiler construction
#   * Predecessor: RML (Relational Meta-Language), which gave omc its
#     unusual `-`-prefixed runtime flags
#   * The OpenModelica compiler is BOOTSTRAPPED: omc.exe is compiled
#     from MetaModelica source by omc.exe itself (after an initial
#     C-translated bootstrap pass)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE OPENMODELICA `omc` CLI — RML/MetaModelica TWO-PREFIX ARGV PARSER
#
# OpenModelica's omc binary uses a TWO-PREFIX argv convention:
#
#   * `+flag`     — omcOptions (compiler/MetaModelica-level)
#   * `+flag=val` — omcOptions with value
#   * `-flag`     — runtimeOptions (RML runtime / GC / debug)
#   * `-flag=val` — runtimeOptions with value
#
# This is INHERITED FROM RML (Relational Meta-Language), the original
# OpenModelica meta-language by Peter Fritzson and Pavol Pilar in
# 1995-2000.  RML used `-` for its own runtime options (GC, stack,
# trace) and OpenModelica added `+` for compiler-level flags so the
# two sets wouldn't collide.
#
# Distinct from every other documented argv-parsing library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. `+` PREFIX FOR COMPILER FLAGS — Every other documented argv
#      parser in the taxonomy uses `-`/`--` exclusively.  OpenModelica
#      omc is the FIRST documented library that uses `+` as the
#      primary compiler-flag prefix.  This is a deliberate choice to
#      separate compile-time options from runtime/RML options, neither
#      conflicting with file paths (`-` is also used for stdin in
#      Unix) nor with the runtime's `-`-prefixed flags.
#
#   2. TWO-PREFIX SCHEMA — Most argv parsers use ONE prefix style
#      (clap/cobra/argparse: `-`/`--`; Factor: `-`).  OpenModelica
#      uses TWO prefixes for TWO different runtime layers: the
#      MetaModelica compiler layer (`+`) and the RML runtime layer
#      (`-`).  When the user runs `omc +s Model.mo -log -stack-size=
#      8M`, the `+s` is interpreted by the MetaModelica `Flags`
#      module while `-log` and `-stack-size` are interpreted by the
#      C-translated RML runtime before MetaModelica code even runs.
#      First documented two-prefix argv schema.
#
#   3. SELF-HOSTED METAMODELICA FLAG REGISTRY — The `Compiler/Util/
#      Flags.mo` file (in MetaModelica) defines every `+flag` via a
#      `CONFIG_FLAG` record.  When the user passes `+annotationVersion
#      =2.x`, MetaModelica pattern-matches the string against the
#      registry, validates the value (must be 1.x/2.x/3.x), and
#      stores it in the global `Flags` namespace.  Reads like Haskell
#      case-of, but is written in MetaModelica's algebraic-data-type
#      pattern-matching syntax — a unique language with no Haskell-
#      interpreter.
#
#   4. DEBUG SUBFLAGS VIA `+d=NAME` — The OpenModelica compiler has
#      150+ named debug flags (`+d=parseonly`, `+d=parsedump`,
#      `+d=failtrace`, `+d=bltdump`, `+d=interactive`, ...) all
#      multiplexed through a single `+d` flag.  Compare clap's
#      `#[arg(short = 'v', long = "verbose", action = ArgAction::
#      Count)]` (counted) or Cobra's individual flag fields —
#      OpenModelica uses a single `+d=` selector parsing a comma-
#      separated list.  Allows arbitrarily many debug flags without
#      exploding the top-level flag namespace.
#
#   5. ANNOTATION VERSION FLAG ON COMPILER — `+annotationVersion=`
#      selects which Modelica Language Specification annotation
#      version to parse (1.x / 2.x / 3.x).  No other documented
#      compiler has a flag for "which version of the language
#      annotation grammar to use" — most compilers have ONE syntax
#      per release.  Modelica has 30+ years of grammar evolution and
#      omc supports parsing files conforming to any.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced from doc/manpages/omc.1, the canonical
# upstream manpage for `omc` shipped with every OpenModelica release.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -C \
    '++v[print version and exit]' \
    '+version[print version and exit]' \
    '+s[generate simulation code]' \
    '+d=-[set debug flags (multiple via comma-separated list)]:flag:->dflags' \
    '+c=-[CORBA session name (works with +d=interactiveCorba)]:name:' \
    '+annotationVersion=-[Modelica annotation version to use]:version:(1.x 2.x 3.x)' \
    '+noSimplify[do not simplify expressions]' \
    '+q[run in quiet mode, output nothing]' \
    '+g=-[accept grammar variant]:grammar:(Modelica MetaModelica)' \
    '-help[print RML runtime options and exit]' \
    '-log[print runtime log information at program exit]' \
    '-gcgag[print garbage-collector log information at program exit]' \
    '-bench[print running time and other log information at exit]' \
    '-no-stack-check[do not check for stack overflow]' \
    '-stack-size=-[allocate runtime stack of specified size]:size:' \
    '-young-size=-[allocate young (nursery) heap of specified size]:size:' \
    '-trace[print all function names during execution (requires -ftrace build)]' \
    '-no-trace[disable printing of function names (requires -ftrace build)]' \
    '-dbgCmdPort=-[localhost port for command channel from debug client]:port:' \
    '-dbgReplyPort=-[localhost port for command replies to debug client]:port:' \
    '-dbgEventPort=-[localhost port for async events to debug client]:port:' \
    '-dbgSignalPort=-[localhost port for async events from debug client]:port:' \
    '-dbgSocket[debug the socket communication]' \
    '-debugAll[dump all calls and variable values (can be extremely large)]' \
    '*:Modelica or MetaModelica source file:_files -g "*.(mo|mof|mos|onb)"' \
    && ret=0

case "$state" in
    dflags)
        local -a dflags
        dflags=(
            'interactive:start omc as a server listening on the socket interface'
            'interactiveCorba:start omc as a server listening on the CORBA interface'
            'bltdump:dump in the BLT (Block Lower Triangular) form'
            'failtrace:print which function fails'
            'parsedump:dump the parsing tree'
            'parseonly:only parse the given file and exit'
            'dynload:display debug info about dynamic loading of compiled functions'
        )
        _describe -t dflags 'omc debug flag' dflags && ret=0
        ;;
esac

return ret
